# LeakSanitizer suppressions for the c47/c43 simulator analysis lanes.
#
# AddressSanitizer is the hard memory gate (ITERATION-3 policy), but a few
# upstream allocations are made once at startup and never freed, so they would
# fail the gate on every run and hide a real regression. Suppress the known ones
# here - tight, by the allocating frame - so a NEW leak still fails the lane.
# Each entry is an upstream bug to file, not a harness defect.

# fnReset -> showSoftmenuCurrentPart -> initVariableSoftmenu ->
# _dynmenuConstructUser (src/c47/softmenus.c:1577): the dynamic VAR softmenu is
# malloc'd on reset and never freed (40 bytes, 1 allocation).
leak:_dynmenuConstructUser

# fnReset -> doFnReset (src/c47/config.c:1578): the not-found-glyph buffer
# (glyphNotFound.data) is malloc'd on reset and never freed (38 bytes, 1
# allocation). Newly exercised by the merged coverage corpus. Real one-shot
# upstream leak; fix pending on c43 branch fix/restore-glyphnotfound-leak
# (MR !1485). Remove this entry once that MR merges upstream.
leak:doFnReset

# GTK/GUI toolkit caches. The analysis lane launches the real GTK app
# (./c47 --writeexportall, ./r47 --writeexportall under xvfb); on exit the
# toolkit's font/layout/widget caches are never torn down, so LeakSanitizer
# reports ~950 blocks (~1.5 MB) allocated entirely inside fontconfig, pango,
# cairo, gdk and gtk-3 - process-global caches reclaimed by the OS, not c47
# bugs. Every one of these blocks bottoms out in c47 only as the call site that
# rendered text (gtkGui.c moveLabels/calcModeAimGui); the allocation itself is
# always in a toolkit frame. Suppress by toolkit module so a genuine c47-origin
# leak (one whose allocating frame is in src/c47) still fails the lane. Note we
# deliberately do NOT suppress glib/gobject/gio: no leak block depends solely on
# those, and c47 could allocate through them directly, so leaving them gated
# keeps real c47 leaks visible.
leak:libfontconfig
leak:libpango
leak:libcairo
leak:libgdk
leak:libgtk-3
